   "source": [
    "There are two main types of data:\n",
    "\n",
    "Qualitative (Categorical) Data: Qualitative data represents categories or labels and cannot be measured numerically. It can be divided into two subtypes:\n",
    "\n",
    "Nominal Data: Categories have no natural order or ranking. Example: Colors (red, green, blue).\n",
    "Ordinal Data: Categories have a natural order or ranking but the differences between them are not meaningful. Example: Educational levels (high school, college, graduate).\n",
    "Quantitative (Numerical) Data: Quantitative data represents measurable quantities and can be measured numerically. It can be divided into two subtypes:\n",
    "\n",
    "Discrete Data: Consists of distinct, separate values that can be counted. Example: Number of cars in a parking lot.\n",
    "Continuous Data: Represents measurements on a continuous scale and can take any value within a given range. Example: Height, temperature."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "f1d4378c-21a0-4734-86de-bac64647ed90",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "(i) Grading in exam: Qualitative (Ordinal) - There is an order (A > B > C) but the differences between grades are not meaningful.\n",
    "\n",
    "(ii) Color of mangoes: Qualitative (Nominal) - The colors represent categories with no natural order.\n",
    "\n",
    "(iii) Height data of a class: Quantitative (Continuous) - Heights can take on any value within a range.\n",
    "\n",
    "(iv) Number of mangoes exported by a farm: Quantitative (Discrete) - The number of mangoes is a count and consists of distinct values."
   ]
  },
